	.articleContent
		p Tabs have a very infrequent use case, so should be avoided where the content may better work in revealable. It's important to keep in mind that tabs shouldn't be used with more than 3-4 tabs, and display as normal content on mobile.
		p Because tab functionality is removed on mobile (and browsers without Javascript), it's important to never use the tab text as a title, as it won't be visible to everyone. Generally, tabs should have shorter titles than content anyway.
		h2 Accessibility
		p Accessibility is an important part of using tabs. This means that the syntax needs to work well for keyboard users and screen readers. This means that all the Javascript and CSS is based around aria attributes, to distinguish the active tab.
		p An important inclusion is being able to use the arrow keys to navigate between tabs, as well as the tab key.
		.example-box-plain
			ul.tablist(role='tablist')
				li#tab1.tab(aria-controls='panel1', aria-selected='true', role='tab', tabindex='0') Tab one
				li#tab2.tab(aria-controls='panel2', role='tab', aria-selected='false', tabindex='0') Tab two
				li#tab3.tab(aria-controls='panel3', role='tab', aria-selected='false', tabindex='0') Tab three
			#panel1.tab-panel(aria-labelledby='tab1', role='tabpanel', aria-hidden='false')
				h3 Tab one
				p Lorem ipsum dolor sit amet, consectetur adipiscing elit. Mauris sit amet nibh sed magna sollicitudin ultricies.
			#panel2.tab-panel(aria-labelledby='tab2', role='tabpanel', aria-hidden='true')
				h3 Tab two
				p Morbi velit arcu, molestie blandit mi sit amet, laoreet accumsan elit. Etiam quis ullamcorper nibh, pulvinar congue neque. Duis porttitor tellus enim, porta sagittis dui consequat non.
			#panel3.tab-panel(aria-labelledby='tab3', role='tabpanel', aria-hidden='true')
				h3 Tab three
				p Aliquam pharetra feugiat velit, sed gravida tortor consequat vel.
